00:36:47.300 --> 00:36:48.660
in front of 20 million people,

00:36:48.660 --> 00:36:50.600
I could pretty much do anything
I wanted to.

00:36:55.200 --> 00:36:58.060
ANNOUNCER:
Go ahead and drool,
it's Miss America time.

00:37:00.400 --> 00:37:02.760
NARRATOR:
For more than a quarter century,

00:37:02.760 --> 00:37:04.330
the bathing suit competition

00:37:04.330 --> 00:37:07.430
had been the Miss America
Pageant's feature attraction.

00:37:07.430 --> 00:37:11.130
But with the scholarship program
now in place,

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:15.500
Lenora Slaughter wanted to
project a more dignified image.

00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:18.200
The challenge was to downplay
the bathing suits

00:37:18.200 --> 00:37:20.360
without offending
Catalina Swimwear,

00:37:20.360 --> 00:37:22.630
one of the pageant's
major sponsors.

00:37:24.060 --> 00:37:28.300
In 1947, Slaughter struck
the term "bathing suit"

00:37:28.300 --> 00:37:30.260
from the official
pageant vocabulary,

00:37:30.260 --> 00:37:35.500
and replaced it with the more
athletic-sounding "swimsuit."

00:37:35.500 --> 00:37:39.660
Then she banned two-piece suits
from the competition,

00:37:39.660 --> 00:37:43.060
and announced that Miss America
would now be crowned

00:37:43.060 --> 00:37:45.200
in an evening gown.

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:48.660
Still, when most Americans
thought of the pageant,

00:37:48.660 --> 00:37:50.100
a girl in a bathing suit

00:37:50.100 --> 00:37:52.430
was the first thing
that came to mind.

00:37:54.660 --> 00:37:56.700
Then along came Yolande Betbeze.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:02.700
A 21-year-old opera singer
from Mobile, Alabama,

00:38:02.700 --> 00:38:06.360
Betbeze had been recently sprung
from convent school

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:12.430
when she captured her first
local crown, Miss Torch 1949.

00:38:12.430 --> 00:38:16.230
Miss Alabama wasn't far behind.

00:38:16.230 --> 00:38:20.030
WOMAN:
I didn't plan
on the Miss America Pageant.

00:38:20.030 --> 00:38:22.060
I didn't know anything about it.

00:38:22.060 --> 00:38:25.330
I was in a convent for 14 years.

00:38:25.330 --> 00:38:26.600
The last four years

00:38:26.600 --> 00:38:30.930
in a cloistered convent,
behind high walls,

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:32.730
and no escape.

00:38:34.230 --> 00:38:38.030
And I was very naive
when I arrived in Atlantic City.

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:41.300
I mean, coming from a small town
in Alabama,

00:38:41.300 --> 00:38:44.000
borrowing shoes of high heels,

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.030
and taking the braces
off my teeth,

00:38:46.030 --> 00:38:47.430
I had a ball.

00:38:49.630 --> 00:38:53.360
NARRATOR:
The minute Betbeze stepped
off the train in Atlantic City,

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:56.830
Slaughter knew she was looking
at the next Miss America.

00:38:56.830 --> 00:38:58.500
♪ Now give us fever. ♪

00:38:58.500 --> 00:39:01.860
