00:40:54.460 --> 00:40:57.260
"is not my idea of Miss America.

00:40:57.260 --> 00:41:00.630
Scholarship foundation,
the reason I'm here."

00:41:00.630 --> 00:41:04.260
And he really, really thought
I had lost my mind.

00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:05.800
He couldn't believe it.

00:41:05.800 --> 00:41:09.660
FERENTZ:
I love the fact
that she made the statement

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:12.830
that she had to play their game
to become Miss America,

00:41:12.830 --> 00:41:14.260
and once she became
Miss America,

00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:16.700
they had to play by her game.

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:19.030
I thought it was
very bold of her

00:41:19.030 --> 00:41:22.230
to say to one of its major
sponsors, which was Catalina,

00:41:22.230 --> 00:41:25.330
that she just wasn't going
to pose in a swimsuit.

00:41:25.330 --> 00:41:27.730
That she was an opera singer,
she was not a pinup.

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:33.230
NARRATOR:
Catalina withdrew its
sponsorship of Miss America,

00:41:33.230 --> 00:41:37.560
and soon launched not one,
but two pageants of its own--

00:41:37.560 --> 00:41:40.600
Miss U.S.A. and Miss Universe.

00:41:40.600 --> 00:41:44.600
Both judged contestants entirely
on looks

00:41:44.600 --> 00:41:48.600
and absolutely required them
to wear Catalina swimsuits.

00:41:50.060 --> 00:41:52.360
LEVI:
For the pageant,
there was always this pull

00:41:52.360 --> 00:41:55.900
between the pulchritude
and the pulpit.

00:41:55.900 --> 00:41:57.930
There was always
this sort of dichotomy about,

00:41:57.930 --> 00:42:01.530
"How are you an upstanding,
religious, well-educated girl,

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:03.630
and you can show
your thighs and cleavage?"

00:42:03.630 --> 00:42:05.930
Which is always kind of
a theme of America anyhow,

00:42:05.930 --> 00:42:08.700
sexuality and godliness.

00:42:08.700 --> 00:42:10.500
The Elvis Presley phenomenon:

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:12.930
shake your hips while singing
"Nearer My God to Thee."

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:20.400
NARRATOR:
In the fall of 1952,
the pageant's directors invited

00:42:20.400 --> 00:42:22.160
an up-and-coming
Hollywood actress

00:42:22.160 --> 00:42:23.600
named Marilyn Monroe

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:27.400
to serve as the grand marshal
of the Boardwalk Parade.

00:42:30.100 --> 00:42:32.800
"She wore the first dress
anybody had ever worn,"

00:42:32.800 --> 00:42:35.100
that year's Miss America said
later,

00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:37.830
"that was cut down
to her navel."

00:42:39.360 --> 00:42:44.260
Monroe was not asked back
to Atlantic City.

00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:51.030
It had taken
nearly three decades

00:42:51.030 --> 00:42:54.400
to transform Miss America
from a local celebrity

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:57.630
to a national phenomenon.

00:42:57.630 --> 00:43:01.700
But making her a household name
would take just one night,

00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:06.830
September 11th, 1954,

00:43:06.830 --> 00:43:09.230
when Miss America
would be crowned live

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:12.430
on national television.

00:43:12.430 --> 00:43:14.660
The pageant's board of directors
had asked

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:16.830
former Miss America Bess Myerson

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:21.130
to provide backstage commentary
for the viewers at home,

00:43:21.130 --> 00:43:23.330
