Academy Award-winning actress
Grace Kelly

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:26.800
to judge the competition.

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:29.100
ANNOUNCER:
...plenty of excitement
out front, too, Bess.

00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:31.730
Just a while ago, the judges
announced the ten semifinal...

00:43:31.730 --> 00:43:35.130
NARRATOR:
Now, as the cameras wheeled
into position

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:37.930
on Atlantic City's
Convention Hall stage,

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:40.230
ABC sent out
the broadcast signal,

00:43:40.230 --> 00:43:43.560
and television audiences
coast to coast

00:43:43.560 --> 00:43:47.000
joined the Miss America finals
already in progress.

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:56.160
WOMAN:
The only time
I really noticed a camera was,

00:43:56.160 --> 00:43:58.060
we were waiting
to have the crowning.

00:43:58.060 --> 00:44:01.760
I saw a television camera,
and it was coming toward us,

00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:04.160
so I thought,
"Oh, it's, it's time."

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:07.930
And then I saw Lenora Slaughter,
the head of the pageant,

00:44:07.930 --> 00:44:11.360
bringing a banner over,
and she put it on my lap.

00:44:11.360 --> 00:44:14.400
She said,
"Lee, you're our Miss America."

00:44:14.400 --> 00:44:17.630
ANNOUNCER:
19-year-old Lee Ann Meriwether
of San Francisco, California.

00:44:19.560 --> 00:44:23.760
My head flipped back,
and that is all I remember.

00:44:23.760 --> 00:44:26.430
And I was crying hysterically.

00:44:26.430 --> 00:44:29.000
Crying, crying, I couldn't stop.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:31.400
But I do remember my mother
being pulled backstage.

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:33.100
And my mother said,

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.660
(<i> whispering</i> ):
"Stop your sniveling."

00:44:35.660 --> 00:44:38.130
(<i> snaps fingers</i> ):
And that did it.

00:44:38.130 --> 00:44:40.560
NARRATOR:
More than 27 million people,

00:44:40.560 --> 00:44:43.160
nearly half
of the television audience,

00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:46.500
watched the Miss America Pageant
that night,

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:49.930
in a broadcast that broke
all records for TV viewership.

00:44:49.930 --> 00:44:53.630
"To think that folks
out in Idaho could see this

00:44:53.630 --> 00:44:57.100
was just amazing,"
one pageant volunteer recalled.

00:44:57.100 --> 00:45:01.130
"It just knocked everything
off the airwaves."

00:45:01.130 --> 00:45:02.960
MAN:
The Miss America contest
was something

00:45:02.960 --> 00:45:05.000
that seemed very glamorous
to all of us

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.700
in the '30s and '40s and '50s.

00:45:07.700 --> 00:45:09.030
But all we ever saw of it

00:45:09.030 --> 00:45:11.560
were snippets on newsreels
in movie theaters.

00:45:11.560 --> 00:45:13.760
And then suddenly,
when television happened,

00:45:13.760 --> 00:45:16.200
here was this fabulous event,

00:45:16.200 --> 00:45:18.860
and in that period,
it was incredibly popular.

00:45:18.860 --> 00:45:21.530
When you look at old
black-and-white television now

00:45:21.530 --> 00:45:22.930
it looks so prehistoric,

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:25.330
but, my God, it was free,
it was in your house,

00:45:25.330 --> 00:45:26.330
you could watch it.

00:45:26.330 --> 00:45:27.700
And it changed everything.

00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:30.060
ANNOUNCER:
The<i> Miss America Pageant,</i>

00:45:30.060 --> 00:45:32.560
brought to you
by Philco Corporation.

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:34.630
NARRATOR:
By the second broadcast,

00:45:34.630 --> 00:45:37.060
the pageant had been
redesigned for TV,

00:45:37.060 --> 00:45:40.660
and a celebrity singer
and announcer had been hired

00:45:40.660 --> 00:45:43.830
to serve as the regular
master of ceremonies.

00:45:43.830 --> 00:45:45.260
The 40-year-old star

00:45:45.260 --> 00:45:48.600
of a popular TV program called
<i> Stop the Music,</i>

00:45:48.600 --> 00:45:51.700
he was known to audiences
across the country

00:45:51.700 --> 00:45:54.660
as the guy with the smile
you can read by.

00:45:54.660 --> 00:45:57.530
His name was Bert Parks.

00:45:57.530 --> 00:45:59.100
MAN:
Bert Parks.

00:45:59.100 --> 00:46:00.460
(<i> applause</i> )

00:46:00.460 --> 00:46:02.600
Thank you very much.

00:46:02.600 --> 00:46:04.800
(<i> applause</i> )

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:06.400
Thank you. Good evening.

00:46:06.400 --> 00:46:08.360
You're a wonderful audience.

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:10.960
HORN:
Bert Parks came along
at just the right time.

00:46:10.960 --> 00:46:18.230
And his ability to be funny, to
be extemporaneous, to be silly,

00:46:18.230 --> 00:46:19.730
and yet at the same time,

00:46:19.730 --> 00:46:25.900
allow the women to be
the stars of the show

00:46:25.900 --> 00:46:28.460
was a perfect series
of ingredients

00:46:28.460 --> 00:46:30.960
that the Miss America program
needed at that time.

00:46:30.960 --> 00:46:39.260
(<i> orchestra playing
 "Ain't She Sweet"</i> )

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:40.760
That's fine. Thank you.

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:43.200
(<i> applause</i> )

00:46:43.200 --> 00:46:46.860
And this, of course,
ladies and gentlemen,
is Miss Oklahoma.

00:46:46.860 --> 00:46:48.360
From what city,
please?

00:46:48.360 --> 00:46:50.260
I'm from Alva,
Oklahoma.

00:46:50.260 --> 00:46:51.330
Alva?

00:46:51.330 --> 00:46:52.530
Alva.

00:46:52.530 --> 00:46:54.500
What is the
population of Alva?

00:46:54.500 --> 00:46:55.730
7,000.

00:46:55.730 --> 00:46:57.000
7,000.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.430
What is Alva
most famous for,
Miss Oklahoma?

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:01.800
Wheat and cattle

00:47:01.800 --> 00:47:03.660
and my daddy's
bakery.

00:47:03.660 --> 00:47:06.300
(<i> laughter</i> )

00:47:06.300 --> 00:47:09.300
Golden Krust Bakery;
call him up tonight.

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:10.700
(<i> laughter</i> )

00:47:10.700 --> 00:47:12.860
LEVI:
I don't know
if he would fly today,

00:47:12.860 --> 00:47:15.430
but he was really into
the girls, the women,

00:47:15.430 --> 00:47:18.100
and that's what made Bert Parks
so different.

00:47:18.100 --> 00:47:20.700
He wasn't a celebrity flown in
on a Saturday night.

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:22.930
He was there all week
getting to know them.

00:47:22.930 --> 00:47:23.930
They trusted him.

00:47:23.930 --> 00:47:25.930
He loved what he was doing,

00:47:25.930 --> 00:47:29.200
and he really was one
of the defining factors

00:47:29.200 --> 00:47:32.530
that made households
and television households

00:47:32.530 --> 00:47:34.630
love Miss America.

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:38.630
And when he sang "There She Is,"
that was it.

00:47:38.630 --> 00:47:39.930
There she<i> was.</i>

00:47:39.930 --> 00:47:43.300
And now, Miss America
of 1958,

00:47:43.300 --> 00:47:45.660
there is the runway.

00:47:45.660 --> 00:47:48.360
There are
your subjects.

00:47:48.360 --> 00:47:51.430
(<i> orchestra plays intro
 to "There She Is"</i> )

00:47:51.430 --> 00:47:55.600
PARKS:
♪ Oh, there she is ♪

00:47:55.600 --> 00:48:00.360
♪ Miss America. ♪

00:48:00.360 --> 00:48:03.900
NARRATOR:
Making its debut
right alongside Parks

00:48:03.900 --> 00:48:07.030
was the official
Miss America theme song.

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:09.330
Composed in just under an hour

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:12.660
by a New York songwriter
named Bernie Wayne,

00:48:12.660 --> 00:48:14.860
the song was an instant hit.

00:48:14.860 --> 00:48:19.130
It would soon be as recognizable
as the national anthem.

00:48:19.130 --> 00:48:24.430
PARKS:
♪ For she may turn out to be ♪

00:48:24.430 --> 00:48:28.260
♪ The queen of femininity. ♪

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:30.400
PEISS:
It evokes a wedding

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:34.860
with Bert Parks kind of giving
away the... the bride,

00:48:34.860 --> 00:48:38.400
or, in his youth,
he was more of the groom.

00:48:38.400 --> 00:48:42.060
It evokes the debutante ball.

00:48:42.060 --> 00:48:45.000
PARKS:
♪ ...Who are more than pretty ♪

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:47.860
♪ Can come true
in Atlantic City. ♪

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:50.160
PEISS:
There is this real sense

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:53.160
of suddenly being the most
beautiful woman at the ball.

00:48:53.160 --> 00:48:56.030
And so there is this sense that
this could happen to anyone,

00:48:56.030 --> 00:48:57.600
or at least that's the fantasy--

00:48:57.600 --> 00:48:59.330
that this could happen
to any girl.

00:48:59.330 --> 00:49:02.000
PARKS:
♪ ...Sweetheart. ♪

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:05.860
There she is, ladies and
gentlemen, Miss America.

00:49:05.860 --> 00:49:07.630
(<i> applause</i> )

00:49:09.460 --> 00:49:11.530
ALVAREZ:
We didn't see a whole lot

00:49:11.530 --> 00:49:14.230
of what it was like
to be an American woman.

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:17.660
This was our little window
into what it was like,

00:49:17.660 --> 00:49:19.460
what this world was like.

00:49:19.460 --> 00:49:23.700
It was a way to, I don't know,
climb the ladder of success.

00:49:23.700 --> 00:49:25.830
And so, you know, it was like

00:49:25.830 --> 00:49:29.660
watching a female version
of a Horatio Alger story.

00:49:29.660 --> 00:49:32.700
I had no knowledge
of the pageant really at all.

00:49:32.700 --> 00:49:35.560
I knew that there was
a Miss America Pageant,

00:49:35.560 --> 00:49:39.700
but I thought it was
a "bathing beauty contest,"

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:44.600
and as such,
I would never have entered.

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:47.260
And then my father passed away,

00:49:47.260 --> 00:49:51.330
and just, my life
sort of stopped right there.

00:49:51.330 --> 00:49:55.860
And my mother said, "The money
is no longer here, daddy's gone,

00:49:55.860 --> 00:50:00.430
"and if you want to continue on
with school, that's the thing.

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:03.060
Go to Atlantic City."

00:50:03.060 --> 00:50:05.460
STEINEM:
Beauty contests are ways that,

00:50:05.460 --> 00:50:07.600
if you live in
a poor neighborhood,

00:50:07.600 --> 00:50:10.900
you can imagine getting ahead
because it is a way up.

00:50:10.900 --> 00:50:13.230
It is a way to scholarships,
to attention,

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:16.160
and it's one of the few things
that you see out there

00:50:16.160 --> 00:50:17.330
as a popular symbol.

00:50:17.330 --> 00:50:18.800
When I was living

00:50:18.800 --> 00:50:23.200
in a kind of factory working
neighborhood of Toledo,

00:50:23.200 --> 00:50:27.960
the K-Part Television Miss TV
Contest, something like that,

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:30.030
was advertised.

00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:32.460
So I decided I would try
to enter the contest

00:50:32.460 --> 00:50:33.960
even though I was underage.

00:50:33.960 --> 00:50:36.430
I think I was 16 and the limit
was... was 18.

00:50:36.430 --> 00:50:37.730
So I lied about my age.

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:40.860
It wasn't a terrible experience.

00:50:40.860 --> 00:50:44.000
It was a surrealistic
experience.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:47.200
You had to put on
your bathing suit and walk

00:50:47.200 --> 00:50:49.000
and stand on a beer keg.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:53.200
I did, you know, three or four
different kinds of dances.

00:50:53.200 --> 00:50:56.260
Spanish and Russian
and heaven knows what.

00:50:56.260 --> 00:50:58.660
I thought I'd get money
for college,

00:50:58.660 --> 00:51:00.400
and it seemed glamorous.

00:51:00.400 --> 00:51:02.600
It seemed to me, in high school,

00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:05.160
like a way out
of a not-too-great life

00:51:05.160 --> 00:51:07.260
in a pretty poor neighborhood.

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:16.960
NARRATOR:
By 1958, Atlantic City's
local tourist attraction

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:20.230
had become one of the most
popular television events

00:51:20.230 --> 00:51:21.860
in the country.

00:51:21.860 --> 00:51:25.400
With networks competing
over the broadcasting contract

00:51:25.400 --> 00:51:26.960
and companies clamoring

00:51:26.960 --> 00:51:30.530
to provide the high-profile
program with sponsorship,

00:51:30.530 --> 00:51:33.600
the Miss America Pageant
could now afford

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:37.000
to award over $200,000 worth
of scholarships.

00:51:38.360 --> 00:51:39.900
But winning money for college

00:51:39.900 --> 00:51:41.900
was only part
of the pageant's appeal.

00:51:41.900 --> 00:51:43.960
As every contestant knew,

00:51:43.960 --> 00:51:47.960
being crowned Miss America
on national television

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:52.630
could turn a small-town girl
into an instant celebrity.

00:51:52.630 --> 00:51:55.900
(<i> applause</i> )

00:51:55.900 --> 00:51:58.460
I'm sure you all realize,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:51:58.460 --> 00:52:01.800
what a frightening experience
it is for these young ladies,

00:52:01.800 --> 00:52:05.600
most of whom have never appeared
in public before,

00:52:05.600 --> 00:52:09.760
much less here in the convention
hall in Atlantic City

00:52:09.760 --> 00:52:14.460
before some 25,000 people and
over a full television network.

00:52:14.460 --> 00:52:18.660
NARRATOR:
One of the contestants
that year was Mary Ann Mobley,

00:52:18.660 --> 00:52:23.330
a 19-year-old drama major with
her eye on the Broadway stage.

00:52:23.330 --> 00:52:27.800
A native of Brandon,
Mississippi-- population 2,500--

00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:32.230
Mobley had competed in her first
pageant only two weeks before,

00:52:32.230 --> 00:52:35.260
at the personal request
of Brandon's mayor,

00:52:35.260 --> 00:52:38.100
and had walked off
with the state title.

00:52:38.100 --> 00:52:41.230
PARKS:
Miss Mississippi.

00:52:41.230 --> 00:52:42.330
(<i> applause</i> )

00:52:42.330 --> 00:52:44.130
WOMAN:
Everyone was in shock.

00:52:44.130 --> 00:52:46.300
I said to my Sunday school
teacher,

00:52:46.300 --> 00:52:50.000
I said, "I can't believe I'm
on the way to Atlantic City."

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:53.630
I mean, I had seen
the previous Miss America.

00:52:53.630 --> 00:52:55.730
She was tall.

00:52:55.730 --> 00:52:59.560
I mean, her legs started
at my armpits.

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:05.400
And she had these wonderful
features and long blonde hair,

00:53:05.400 --> 00:53:09.000
and I thought that's what
Miss America should look like

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:10.760
and I'm nowhere near that.

00:53:10.760 --> 00:53:13.430
And now, ladies and gentlemen,

00:53:13.430 --> 00:53:16.100
we come to the talent
competition.

00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:17.830
MOBLEY:
Now I have to tell you

00:53:17.830 --> 00:53:21.260
that I had never sung
with an orchestra.

00:53:21.260 --> 00:53:27.430
And there I was in front of two
football fields put together.

00:53:27.430 --> 00:53:29.630
Well, I was panicked.

00:53:29.630 --> 00:53:33.060
And my horror was,
I was going to get out there

00:53:33.060 --> 00:53:35.630
and no sound
was going to come out.

00:53:35.630 --> 00:53:39.330
And one of the stagehands
tapped me on the shoulder

00:53:39.330 --> 00:53:42.800
and he said,
"You go get 'em, Mississippi."

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:43.800
Let's bring her on.

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:45.260
(<i> applause</i> )

00:53:45.260 --> 00:53:48.230
MOBLEY:
And they swagged the curtain,

00:53:48.230 --> 00:53:51.100
and I thought,
I've got two options:

00:53:51.100 --> 00:53:53.830
I can run,
or I can walk out there.

00:53:53.830 --> 00:53:58.100
And I said I can't embarrass
my home state and myself

00:53:58.100 --> 00:54:00.160
by running away.

00:54:00.160 --> 00:54:03.030
I have to walk out there.

00:54:06.830 --> 00:54:08.700
Tonight as my talent,

00:54:08.700 --> 00:54:12.760
L!ACG a portion
of the lovely "Un Bel Di"

00:54:12.760 --> 00:54:16.300
from Puccini's opera,
<i> Madam Butterfly?</i>

00:54:18.100 --> 00:54:24.830
♪<i> Un bel di vedremo...</i> ♪

00:54:24.830 --> 00:54:33.800
MOBLEY:
And I started "Un bel di," and
it came out and it sounded okay.

00:54:33.800 --> 00:54:38.360
♪<i> ...Mo confin del mare...</i> ♪

00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:39.900
And then I said "Stop.

00:54:39.900 --> 00:54:42.860
"But I'm tired of being
proper and cultured

00:54:42.860 --> 00:54:46.260
and of appreciating
Beethoven, Puccini and Bach."

00:54:46.260 --> 00:54:54.160
I want to sing and dance to
something that's solid and hot.

00:54:54.160 --> 00:54:59.500
So there are gonna be
some changes made.

00:54:59.500 --> 00:55:01.060
MOBLEY:
I said,

00:55:01.060 --> 00:55:09.060
♪ There'll be a change
in the weather ♪

00:55:09.060 --> 00:55:12.000
♪ And a change in the sea ♪

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:17.060
♪ And from now on,
there'll be a change in me. ♪

00:55:17.060 --> 00:55:18.160
(<i> applause</i> )

00:55:18.160 --> 00:55:21.430
MOBLEY:
They started to applaud.

00:55:21.430 --> 00:55:24.500
♪ ...My dress and my name ♪

00:55:24.500 --> 00:55:28.930
♪ Nothing about me's
gonna be the same. ♪

00:55:33.500 --> 00:55:37.660
MOBLEY:
I said, they like me,
or else they're just applauding

00:55:37.660 --> 00:55:40.360
that I'm not going
to finish the aria.

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:51.230
♪ ...Change in me! ♪

00:55:51.230 --> 00:55:55.200
(<i> applause</i> )

00:55:55.200 --> 00:55:57.860
PARKS:
Mary Ann Mobley!

00:55:57.860 --> 00:56:00.800
FERENTZ:
I think Mary Ann
was very popular

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:02.660
because she was different.

00:56:02.660 --> 00:56:06.830
She was tiny and spunky
and had a little bit of guts.

00:56:06.830 --> 00:56:10.630
PARKS:
Here is your question,
Miss Mississippi.

00:56:10.630 --> 00:56:12.930
What is your
favorite topic,

00:56:12.930 --> 00:56:14.700
when with
a young man,

00:56:14.700 --> 00:56:17.100
for opening
the conversation?

00:56:19.360 --> 00:56:21.530
Well, I've read
different articles

00:56:21.530 --> 00:56:25.000
that tell you how to get
along with the opposite sex,

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:27.330
and the first
thing that they say is,

00:56:27.330 --> 00:56:29.330
get him to talk about himself.

00:56:29.330 --> 00:56:32.730
So the first thing I ask is,
"Do you play football?"

00:56:32.730 --> 00:56:35.200
or "What sport are you
interested in?"

00:56:35.200 --> 00:56:36.960
And then if he doesn't
say anything,

00:56:36.960 --> 00:56:39.200
then you say, "Well,
what are your hobbies?"

00:56:39.200 --> 00:56:41.200
And then you go down the line
from there

00:56:41.200 --> 00:56:43.900
and if you can't get him
to answer you on any of those,

00:56:43.900 --> 00:56:46.500
then you're just quiet
for the rest of the evening.

00:56:46.500 --> 00:56:48.900
(<i> laughter</i> )

00:56:48.900 --> 00:56:52.000
(<i> applause</i> )

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:56.200
FERENTZ:
I think that she showed a
different side to Miss America,

00:56:56.200 --> 00:56:58.000
a more girl-next-door type.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:00.730
I think that more young women
could relate to Mary Ann

00:57:00.730 --> 00:57:02.930
than they perhaps could
to the Miss Americas

00:57:02.930 --> 00:57:04.600
that had preceded her.

00:57:04.600 --> 00:57:11.100
PARKS:
First runner up, Joan Lucille
