Miss America: Miss Mississippi!

00:57:14.800 --> 00:57:21.730
(<i> orchestra plays fanfare</i> )

00:57:21.730 --> 00:57:29.730
PARKS:
♪ Oh, there she is,
Miss America ♪

00:57:29.730 --> 00:57:33.660
♪ There she is... ♪

00:57:33.660 --> 00:57:38.860
MOBLEY:
Once I won, I came unglued.

00:57:38.860 --> 00:57:43.560
I mean, I'm not talking
about glistening tears.

00:57:43.560 --> 00:57:49.430
They were running down my chin
onto my chest and my dress.

00:57:49.430 --> 00:57:52.700
CBS ran that for a long time

00:57:52.700 --> 00:57:59.360
because you really saw someone
terribly, terribly affected

00:57:59.360 --> 00:58:03.300
by what was happening
in her life.

00:58:03.300 --> 00:58:09.500
But I remember thinking, what
am I... what am I doing here?

00:58:09.500 --> 00:58:12.830
No one's going to believe this.

00:58:12.830 --> 00:58:17.560
And I'm not pretty enough
to be Miss America,

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:21.660
but here I am
with a crown on my head.

00:58:21.660 --> 00:58:26.230
It's... it's real,
and how could it happen

00:58:26.230 --> 00:58:31.160
to the little girl
from Brandon, Mississippi?

00:58:31.160 --> 00:58:36.430
I think even now
it evokes memories.

00:58:36.430 --> 00:58:41.230
I guess what I was really
feeling was, I was Cinderella.

00:58:47.960 --> 00:58:50.060
(<i> oldies dance music playing</i> )

00:58:50.060 --> 00:58:53.500
ALL:
♪ Everybody's got talent. ♪

00:58:53.500 --> 00:58:55.900
♪ Everybody's got
some kind of talent. ♪

00:58:55.900 --> 00:58:58.560
♪ Everybody's got talent
hidden somewhere ♪

00:58:58.560 --> 00:59:01.100
♪ Hidden somewhere,
hidden somewhere. ♪

00:59:08.460 --> 00:59:11.460
To be pretty and to be talented,
too, now there is a combination.

00:59:12.500 --> 00:59:14.000
WOMAN:
Over the years,

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.830
the talent competition has
become the most significant

00:59:16.830 --> 00:59:19.200
and the most popular part
of this decisive final night.

00:59:21.600 --> 00:59:25.260
The ability to be poised and
personable in the living room

00:59:25.260 --> 00:59:29.060
is a far cry from the ability to
be self-possessed on the stage

00:59:29.060 --> 00:59:30.330
of this great convention hall

00:59:30.330 --> 00:59:33.960
before a live audience
of 25,000 people

00:59:33.960 --> 00:59:36.430
and a television audience
of many millions.

00:59:41.630 --> 00:59:46.930
Now there's a me... that's
really mostly... Cleopatra!

00:59:46.930 --> 00:59:50.630
LEVI:
I do remember a girl
having a talent

00:59:50.630 --> 00:59:53.160
where she told us
how she packed her suitcase.

00:59:53.160 --> 00:59:54.730
I definitely remember that.

00:59:54.730 --> 00:59:56.660
And illustrators were big.

00:59:56.660 --> 00:59:58.560
They had big pieces of paper
clipped on

00:59:58.560 --> 01:00:01.230
and they would quickly do
cartoon sketches and things,

01:00:01.230 --> 01:00:02.400
I remember that.

01:00:02.400 --> 01:00:04.060
WOMAN:
I'm going to do a striptease...

01:00:04.060 --> 01:00:05.330
in reverse.

01:00:09.630 --> 01:00:11.060
GOLDMAN:
I have this great memory

01:00:11.060 --> 01:00:13.460
of this beautiful blonde girl
from Wisconsin

01:00:13.460 --> 01:00:17.260
whose talent was telling a
fishing story with an accent.

01:00:17.260 --> 01:00:18.260
I'm still around,

01:00:18.260 --> 01:00:19.430
I have my pipe...

01:00:19.430 --> 01:00:21.730
got a pole
and line for cast!

01:00:21.730 --> 01:00:24.000
GOLDMAN:
And she was just beautiful.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:26.200
And you were laughing
at the screen even then--

01:00:26.430 --> 01:00:28.500
you couldn't believe that
that was her talent,

01:00:28.500 --> 01:00:30.460
telling a story
with a Norwegian accent.

01:00:30.460 --> 01:00:32.760
I'm competing
for Miss America.

01:00:32.760 --> 01:00:34.400
What are you going to do
for talent?

01:00:34.400 --> 01:00:35.400
(<i> audience laughing</i> )

01:00:36.930 --> 01:00:41.460
Oh, no, no, of course
I believe you...

01:00:41.460 --> 01:00:42.900
I'm not mad...

01:00:42.900 --> 01:00:45.000
MIZRAHI:
I don't really remember
any of the talent

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:48.330
except that it was
always terrible, you know,

01:00:48.330 --> 01:00:49.900
and completely not interesting.

01:00:49.900 --> 01:00:54.200
And that, you know, what I used
to think was a giant flop

01:00:54.200 --> 01:00:56.430
would get the biggest applause.

01:00:56.430 --> 01:00:58.530
Like, I'd sit there thinking,
"Wow, that stank."

01:00:58.530 --> 01:01:00.300
And then the audience
would just go mad,

01:01:00.300 --> 01:01:01.860
loving every second of it.

01:01:01.860 --> 01:01:05.530
(<i> applause, cheering</i> )

01:01:05.530 --> 01:01:07.760
HORN:
A lot of people sat back
and laughed at it.

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:10.830
I thought that was cruel
because here was a young woman

01:01:10.830 --> 01:01:12.960
that was competing
her little heart out

01:01:12.960 --> 01:01:15.500
for a coveted prize
that was important to<i> her.</i>

01:01:15.500 --> 01:01:17.400
That's what the program
was all about.

01:01:17.400 --> 01:01:20.430
It was another reason why it
became so popular

01:01:20.430 --> 01:01:23.830
because it was every woman
and every woman was competing.

01:01:23.830 --> 01:01:26.400
And every woman is not
an accomplished singer

01:01:26.400 --> 01:01:29.030
or an accomplished monologist.

01:01:29.030 --> 01:01:31.730
CHO:
If I had a talent,

01:01:31.730 --> 01:01:33.100
I don't know what I would do.

01:01:33.100 --> 01:01:38.100
I think that I would probably...
collate a script.

01:01:38.100 --> 01:01:39.660
Collate some new pages
in a script.

01:01:39.660 --> 01:01:41.200
That's... I'm really
good at that.

01:01:41.200 --> 01:01:42.600
That's probably my talent.

01:01:42.600 --> 01:01:44.900
Or operating a three-hole punch.

01:01:44.900 --> 01:01:49.130
I can do that pretty swiftly and
I'm probably the best at that.

01:01:49.130 --> 01:01:50.430
What would I do as my talent?

01:01:50.430 --> 01:01:53.860
I would probably sing a song.

01:01:53.860 --> 01:01:56.960
I wouldn't enter, but...

01:01:56.960 --> 01:02:01.160
Now I would, I suppose,
read something I'd written.

01:02:01.160 --> 01:02:02.360
As my talent?

01:02:02.360 --> 01:02:03.900
You know, I worried about that.

01:02:03.900 --> 01:02:06.700
I mean, there was a way in which
I thought I could never be that,

01:02:06.700 --> 01:02:08.460
but it wasn't just
because of the beauty.

01:02:08.460 --> 01:02:11.430
I just didn't have
any displayable talents.

01:02:11.430 --> 01:02:12.430
I couldn't sing.

01:02:12.430 --> 01:02:13.860
I couldn't dance.

01:02:13.860 --> 01:02:17.760
I had an accent, so I couldn't
do a dramatic part.

01:02:17.760 --> 01:02:19.830
And I sort of wondered
what I would do.

01:02:28.860 --> 01:02:30.630
(<i> fanfare playing</i> )

01:02:30.630 --> 01:02:32.860
(<i> applause</i> )

01:02:32.860 --> 01:02:35.100
BERT PARKS:
Susan Brock, Miss California.

01:02:35.100 --> 01:02:40.430
♪ Walking down that runway,
that fabulous runway. ♪

01:02:40.430 --> 01:02:44.460
♪ Her heart is pounding so
on the runway. ♪

01:02:44.460 --> 01:02:46.300
NARRATOR:
By 1960,

01:02:46.300 --> 01:02:50.400
the Miss America Pageant
had become a national ritual.

01:02:50.400 --> 01:02:53.930
Each year, on the second
Saturday in September,

01:02:53.930 --> 01:02:56.330
Americans gathered
in their living rooms,

01:02:56.330 --> 01:02:59.200
switched on their sets,
and settled in to see

01:02:59.200 --> 01:03:03.160
if their favorite contestant
would capture the crown.

01:03:03.160 --> 01:03:05.800
Five times over the next decade,

01:03:05.800 --> 01:03:09.400
the Miss America Pageant was the
highest-rated show of the year.

01:03:09.400 --> 01:03:12.460
PAGEANT ANNOUNCER:
Because with her beauty,
poise, charm and talent,

01:03:12.460 --> 01:03:13.730
the American girl has become

01:03:13.730 --> 01:03:15.330
the most envied girl
in the world.

01:03:15.330 --> 01:03:17.860
NARRATOR:
Richard Nixon claimed
it was the only program

01:03:17.860 --> 01:03:22.260
his daughters were allowed
to stay up late to watch.

01:03:22.260 --> 01:03:24.960
And all across the country now,

01:03:24.960 --> 01:03:29.430
little girls dreamed
of becoming Miss America.

01:03:29.430 --> 01:03:30.830
LEVI:
There was this time--

01:03:30.830 --> 01:03:33.300
what I sort of call the
"debutante era" of the pageant--

01:03:33.300 --> 01:03:35.160
sort of the late '50s,
early '60s,

01:03:35.160 --> 01:03:37.360
when everyone looked like
they were at a cotillion

01:03:37.360 --> 01:03:38.600
with the high white gloves

01:03:38.600 --> 01:03:40.430
and the crinolines
and the big hoop skirts

01:03:40.430 --> 01:03:44.000
and they were for God,
motherhood and apple pie.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:46.860
They wanted to be good mothers,
good wives.

01:03:46.860 --> 01:03:51.130
They wanted to be supporters of
what their husbands chose to do.

01:03:51.130 --> 01:03:52.360
They wanted world peace.

01:03:52.360 --> 01:03:56.300
This is a
presidential election year.

01:03:56.300 --> 01:03:59.960
If a qualified woman
were running for president,

01:03:59.960 --> 01:04:06.660
how would you feel about
voting for her and why?

01:04:06.660 --> 01:04:09.960
If the men candidates running
were qualified,

01:04:09.960 --> 01:04:12.400
I feel I would vote against her.

01:04:12.400 --> 01:04:16.130
My reasons being that women
are very high-strung

01:04:16.130 --> 01:04:18.260
and emotional people.

01:04:18.260 --> 01:04:22.630
They aren't reliable enough when
it comes to making a decision,

01:04:22.630 --> 01:04:24.630
a snap decision.

01:04:24.630 --> 01:04:28.300
I believe that a man
in such a predicament

01:04:28.300 --> 01:04:33.330
would be able to make a more
justifiable and better decision.

01:04:33.330 --> 01:04:37.260
What, in your opinion,
constitutes the ideal wife?

01:04:37.260 --> 01:04:41.830
I imagine that the ideal wife

01:04:41.830 --> 01:04:44.430
depends entirely on
the viewpoint of the husband.

01:04:44.430 --> 01:04:46.430
(<i> applause</i> )

01:04:46.430 --> 01:04:49.430
Some sociologists say
that American women

01:04:49.430 --> 01:04:53.530
are usurping the place of
the male in American life

01:04:53.530 --> 01:04:56.530
and have become
too dominant.

01:04:56.530 --> 01:05:02.660
Do you agree
or disagree, and why?

01:05:02.660 --> 01:05:04.330
I do agree with that.

01:05:04.330 --> 01:05:07.930
I believe that there are far too
many women in the working world.

01:05:07.930 --> 01:05:12.430
I can see many cases where this
is a necessary arrangement,

01:05:12.430 --> 01:05:15.300
but I do feel that a woman's
place is in the home

01:05:15.300 --> 01:05:17.830
with her husband
and with her children.

01:05:17.830 --> 01:05:22.760
HORN:
The concept of Miss America
as an ideal American woman

01:05:22.760 --> 01:05:25.660
was consistent
with society's ideas

01:05:25.660 --> 01:05:27.960
of what an ideal
young woman was.

01:05:27.960 --> 01:05:30.500
She was your everyday young girl

01:05:30.500 --> 01:05:33.160
who any man would be happy
to call daughter,

01:05:33.160 --> 01:05:36.300
any man would be happy
to call wife.

01:05:36.300 --> 01:05:39.830
Miss America was
the American girl-next-door.

01:05:39.830 --> 01:05:44.300
She was an ideal
that many women aspired to.

01:05:44.300 --> 01:05:47.830
NARRATOR:
Until now, the pageant had
managed to present

01:05:47.830 --> 01:05:51.960
a vision of ideal womanhood
that most of the country shared.

01:05:51.960 --> 01:05:56.760
But by the mid-1960s,
the all-American girl-next-door

01:05:56.760 --> 01:05:58.900
was changing fast.

01:05:58.900 --> 01:06:04.230
(<i> Peggy Lee's "I'm a Woman"
 begins playing</i> )

01:06:04.230 --> 01:06:06.400
LEE:
♪ I can wash out
44 pairs of socks ♪

01:06:06.400 --> 01:06:09.260
♪ And have them hanging out
on the line. ♪

01:06:09.260 --> 01:06:11.060
♪ I can starch and iron
two-dozen shirts ♪

01:06:11.060 --> 01:06:14.460
♪ Before you can count
from one to nine. ♪

01:06:14.460 --> 01:06:16.430
♪ I can scoop up a great big
dipper full of lard ♪

01:06:16.430 --> 01:06:18.730
♪ From the drippings can... ♪

01:06:18.730 --> 01:06:21.000
♪ Throw it in the skillet,
go out and do my shopping, ♪

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:22.930
♪ Be back before it melts
in the pan ♪

01:06:22.930 --> 01:06:29.900
♪ 'Cause I'm a woman,
W-O-M-A-N ♪

01:06:29.900 --> 01:06:33.360
♪ I'll say it again. ♪

01:06:33.360 --> 01:06:36.960
NARRATOR:
At a time when bikinis and
miniskirts were all the rage,

01:06:36.960 --> 01:06:39.330
pageant contestants
continued to wear

01:06:39.330 --> 01:06:41.730
the regulation one-piece suits
and dresses

01:06:41.730 --> 01:06:44.860
that fell within two inches
of their knees.

01:06:44.860 --> 01:06:49.160
While antiwar protesters marched
through the nation's streets,

01:06:49.160 --> 01:06:53.130
Miss America was in Vietnam,
touring with the USO.

01:06:53.130 --> 01:06:56.030
And in a moment of
sexual revolution,

01:06:56.030 --> 01:06:59.630
the pageant's ideal remained
wholesome and pure.

01:06:59.630 --> 01:07:03.860
♪ 'Cause I'm a woman,
W-O-M-A-N... ♪

01:07:03.860 --> 01:07:05.760
PEISS:
The pageant bore
no relationship

01:07:05.760 --> 01:07:09.300
to the reality of life in the
United States at that moment:

01:07:09.300 --> 01:07:12.730
the height of the Vietnam War,
a period of great civil unrest,

01:07:12.730 --> 01:07:15.030
the civil rights movement

01:07:15.030 --> 01:07:17.200
and black power movements
at their height,

01:07:17.200 --> 01:07:19.000
and the beginnings
of a feminist movement,

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:22.030
the birth control pill,
the counterculture,

01:07:22.030 --> 01:07:25.630
the origins of the gay and
lesbian liberation movement.

01:07:25.630 --> 01:07:31.200
All of these suggested that the
pageant was terribly out of date

01:07:31.200 --> 01:07:35.530
and that it really was no longer
relevant to the lives of women.

01:07:35.530 --> 01:07:41.300
It was a very exhilarating,
affirming, funny explosion

01:07:41.300 --> 01:07:43.900
of rebellion and consciousness.

01:07:43.900 --> 01:07:46.530
It was partly
about taking off the symbols--

01:07:46.530 --> 01:07:49.230
the gloves,
the little white gloves

01:07:49.230 --> 01:07:50.960
the dyed-to-match shoes--

01:07:50.960 --> 01:07:52.460
and in the middle
of all of that,

01:07:52.460 --> 01:07:55.460
the artificiality of
the Miss America Contest

01:07:55.460 --> 01:07:57.760
was an obvious kind of cartoon.

01:07:59.730 --> 01:08:02.460
NARRATOR:
In the spring of 1968,

01:08:02.460 --> 01:08:05.660
a 27-year-old writer and editor
named Robin Morgan

01:08:05.660 --> 01:08:07.830
decided to take a stand

01:08:07.830 --> 01:08:11.300
and, with help from a group
called "New York Radical Women,"

01:08:11.300 --> 01:08:14.000
she began laying plans
for a protest

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:16.860
at the annual
Miss America Pageant.

01:08:16.860 --> 01:08:20.030
Where else could one find
such a perfect combination

01:08:20.030 --> 01:08:22.930
of American values?
Morgan argued.

01:08:22.930 --> 01:08:26.560
Racism, militarism,
and capitalism

01:08:26.560 --> 01:08:31.960
all packaged in one
ideal symbol: a woman.

01:08:31.960 --> 01:08:33.430
WOMAN:
It seemed to me...

01:08:33.430 --> 01:08:36.000
a sort of epiphany moment

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:40.260
because it was the nexus
of so many issues--

01:08:40.260 --> 01:08:45.030
beauty standards, money,
women's freedom,

01:08:45.030 --> 01:08:47.960
objectification of women,
patriotism--

01:08:47.960 --> 01:08:51.760
and all of this somehow wrapped
up in motherhood and apple pie

01:08:51.760 --> 01:08:54.360
or virginhood and apple pie,
in terms of Miss America.

01:08:54.360 --> 01:08:56.930
So it seemed like,
"My God, you know,

01:08:56.930 --> 01:08:59.300
what is not to dislike
about this?"

01:09:05.260 --> 01:09:08.330
NARRATOR:
Word of the protest soon reached
Atlantic City,

01:09:08.330 --> 01:09:12.360
and pageant organizers braced
themselves for the picket line.

01:09:15.130 --> 01:09:17.460
It would be the first
major demonstration

01:09:17.460 --> 01:09:22.100
of the women's liberation
movement in the United States.

01:09:22.100 --> 01:09:25.230
MORGAN:
We had, you know, prepared
for about maybe 50 people,

01:09:25.230 --> 01:09:26.760
and to do some
guerrilla theater,

01:09:26.760 --> 01:09:27.930
some songs, some chants,

01:09:27.930 --> 01:09:29.900
to picket on the boardwalk
all day.

01:09:29.900 --> 01:09:32.300
What we had not counted on was

01:09:32.300 --> 01:09:34.960
that close to 400 women
showed up.

01:09:34.960 --> 01:09:36.500
And they came from all over.

01:09:36.500 --> 01:09:39.660
I mean they were carrying signs
from Florida and from Wisconsin

01:09:39.660 --> 01:09:41.760
and some people drove
from California,

01:09:41.760 --> 01:09:43.530
and that was just amazing.

01:09:43.530 --> 01:09:44.860
I mean, it had clearly--

01:09:44.860 --> 01:09:46.830
this protest--
tapped into something

01:09:46.830 --> 01:09:51.200
that was enormous and...
and very, very moving.

01:09:51.200 --> 01:09:54.460
WOMAN:
♪ Ain't she quaint ♪

01:09:54.460 --> 01:09:57.900
♪ With her face
all full of paint. ♪

01:09:57.900 --> 01:10:01.460
STEINEM:
They put on the boardwalk
a big trash can

01:10:01.460 --> 01:10:03.060
and dumped in it
all kinds of symbols

01:10:03.060 --> 01:10:05.930
of the stereotypical
female role:

01:10:05.930 --> 01:10:09.030
a steno pad, a dust mop,
an apron, a bra,

01:10:09.030 --> 01:10:10.200
all of these things.

01:10:10.200 --> 01:10:12.630
I think they never did
burn those items

01:10:12.630 --> 01:10:14.500
because they couldn't get
a fire permit--

01:10:14.500 --> 01:10:16.400
just shows you we've been
too law-abiding.

01:10:17.900 --> 01:10:20.230
NARRATOR:
The demonstration
soon drew a crowd

01:10:20.230 --> 01:10:22.000
of more than 600 spectators--

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:26.430
most of them men,
and nearly all unsympathetic.

01:10:26.430 --> 01:10:28.830
One suggested
that the protesters


01:10:28.830 --> 01:10:32.200
throw themselves
into the Freedom Trash Can.

01:10:32.200 --> 01:10:37.300
The threats, the epithets, the
screams, were mostly from guys

01:10:37.300 --> 01:10:40.160
who would, you know, lean over,
the barricades and do the usual.

01:10:40.160 --> 01:10:44.560
I mean to say, sort of, you
know, "Go back to Russia."

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:49.000
"You're commie-pinko-lesbian-
crazy-broom-riding-witches."

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:51.000
You know, you name it.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:53.930
"You're all too ugly to be
in the Miss America Pageant."

01:10:53.930 --> 01:10:58.900
WOMAN:
♪ Ain't she fine. ♪

01:10:58.900 --> 01:11:01.230
NARRATOR:
Inside Convention Hall,

01:11:01.230 --> 01:11:03.530
the Miss America contestants
were running through

01:11:03.530 --> 01:11:06.660
one last rehearsal
before show time.

01:11:06.660 --> 01:11:08.360
Outside, on the Boardwalk,

01:11:08.360 --> 01:11:12.830
the protesters were burning
Bert Parks in effigy.

01:11:12.830 --> 01:11:14.800
Parks was unfazed.

01:11:14.800 --> 01:11:17.800
When he got wind that one of
the demonstrators was planning

01:11:17.800 --> 01:11:20.700
to infiltrate the pageant finals
that evening,

01:11:20.700 --> 01:11:22.500
he didn't miss a beat.

01:11:22.500 --> 01:11:24.860
"I'll grab her by the throat,"
he said,

01:11:24.860 --> 01:11:27.760
"and keep right on singing."

01:11:27.760 --> 01:11:29.860
PARKS:
♪ So don't ever stop seeking ♪

01:11:29.860 --> 01:11:34.530
♪ Don't ever let down. ♪

01:11:34.530 --> 01:11:37.360
♪ Till you you've found
your future ♪

01:11:37.360 --> 01:11:40.960
♪ Till you've captured
your crown. ♪

01:11:40.960 --> 01:11:45.230
NARRATOR:
Judy Ann Ford, an 18-year-old
gymnast from Illinois

01:11:45.230 --> 01:11:49.700
was the first blonde in 11 years
to be crowned Miss America.

01:11:49.700 --> 01:11:53.560
"I'm so glad," she gushed
to the press that evening.

01:11:53.560 --> 01:11:56.660
"I feel like
it's a breakthrough."

01:11:56.660 --> 01:11:59.800
Meanwhile, just four blocks
from Convention Hall

01:11:59.800 --> 01:12:01.530
at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel,

01:12:01.530 --> 01:12:04.030
another ideal
was about to be chosen.

01:12:04.030 --> 01:12:09.360
MALE CHORUS:
♪ Miss Black America...
we're so proud of you... ♪

01:12:09.360 --> 01:12:12.460
NARRATOR:
Calling itself
a "positive protest,"

01:12:12.460 --> 01:12:14.200
the Miss Black America Pageant

01:12:14.200 --> 01:12:16.460
had been scheduled to begin
at midnight

01:12:16.460 --> 01:12:18.660
in the hopes that newsmen
would drop by

01:12:18.660 --> 01:12:20.500
when they left Convention Hall.

01:12:20.500 --> 01:12:22.660
It was nearly
3:00 in the morning

01:12:22.660 --> 01:12:27.330
before 19-year-old Philadelphian
Saundra Williams was crowned.

01:12:27.330 --> 01:12:30.330
MEN:
♪ Miss Black America... ♪

01:12:30.330 --> 01:12:36.060
NARRATOR:
"Miss America does not represent
us," Williams told the audience.

01:12:36.060 --> 01:12:41.630
"With my title, I can show black
women they, too, are beautiful."

01:12:41.630 --> 01:12:44.200
ROSE:
Miss Black America is,
of course, an effort to say

01:12:44.200 --> 01:12:46.260
"Well, look, trying to be
like a white person

01:12:46.260 --> 01:12:47.760
is not what's at stake,

01:12:47.760 --> 01:12:50.130
but appreciating what is black
is quite important."

01:12:50.130 --> 01:12:51.500
So<i> Essence</i> magazine emerges.

01:12:51.500 --> 01:12:54.060
"Black is beautiful," afros,

01:12:54.060 --> 01:12:56.230
you know,
black women emphasizing

01:12:56.230 --> 01:12:58.430
that which is black
as beautiful.

01:12:58.430 --> 01:13:00.700
And so this was a way of saying,

01:13:00.700 --> 01:13:05.200
"We exist as both a market
and as a kind of esthetic"

01:13:05.200 --> 01:13:07.930
really begins to take place
in the late 1960s

01:13:07.930 --> 01:13:10.930
and gets even stronger
in the late-'70s and '80s.

01:13:10.930 --> 01:13:15.930
NARRATOR:
All the controversy of 1968
took its toll on Miss America.

01:13:15.930 --> 01:13:18.360
And before the year was out,

01:13:18.360 --> 01:13:22.500
Pepsi Cola, a sponsor of
the pageant for over 11 years,

01:13:22.500 --> 01:13:24.560
withdrew its support.

01:13:24.560 --> 01:13:28.560
"Miss America as run today,"
the company declared,

01:13:28.560 --> 01:13:32.430
"does not represent the changing
values of our society."

01:13:32.430 --> 01:13:34.360
Society was swirling around it

01:13:34.360 --> 01:13:37.230
but the Miss America pageant
stayed the same,

01:13:37.230 --> 01:13:39.800
continuing to worship
an outmoded ideal.

01:13:39.800 --> 01:13:44.360
In fact, the powers that be
at the pageant never did learn.

01:13:44.360 --> 01:13:47.030
They never did learn.

01:13:47.030 --> 01:13:50.460
They didn't because they regard
the Miss America pageant

01:13:50.460 --> 01:13:52.500
as sacrosanct.

01:13:52.500 --> 01:13:55.500
The Miss America pageant
had developed a formula.

01:13:55.500 --> 01:13:58.600
The formula worked, and
nobody wanted to change it.

01:13:58.600 --> 01:14:00.600
You know,
often I've heard it said

01:14:00.600 --> 01:14:02.500
"Is Miss America
relevant today?"

01:14:02.500 --> 01:14:06.300
Well, is personal achievement
relevant?

01:14:06.300 --> 01:14:07.760
Is scholarship?

01:14:07.760 --> 01:14:09.360
Is good citizenship relevant?

01:14:09.360 --> 01:14:11.100
We think it is.

01:14:11.100 --> 01:14:13.700
And we think it will be
for a long time to come.

01:14:13.700 --> 01:14:17.930
NARRATOR:
The Miss America Pageant still
drew an enormous audience

01:14:17.930 --> 01:14:22.260
reaching a peak, in 1970,
of over 22 million households.

01:14:22.260 --> 01:14:25.000
But then the ratings
started to slip

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:27.630
and the pageant
was finally forced

01:14:27.630 --> 01:14:29.760
to catch up with the times.

01:14:29.760 --> 01:14:31.900
Presenting Cathy Clough,
Lisa Donovan

01:14:31.900 --> 01:14:35.300
and a good friend, and former
Miss America, Phyllis George

01:14:35.300 --> 01:14:37.660
with a comment
on a very timely subject.

01:14:37.660 --> 01:14:38.930
Women, tell it like it is.

01:14:38.930 --> 01:14:40.460
(<i> music begins playing</i> )

01:14:40.460 --> 01:14:43.930
♪ I can fly your plane,
I'll even carry your bags... ♪

01:14:43.930 --> 01:14:47.330
♪ I can clear your drain,
fix your roof if it sags... ♪

01:14:47.330 --> 01:14:51.160
♪ But let me make one thing
perfectly clear ♪

01:14:51.160 --> 01:14:54.960
♪ Don't call me "honey"
and don't call me "dear"... ♪

01:14:54.960 --> 01:15:01.700
ALL:
♪ There's only one little word
that we're waiting to hear ♪

01:15:01.700 --> 01:15:04.060
♪ I want you to call me... ♪

01:15:04.060 --> 01:15:06.360
♪ I said call me... ♪

01:15:06.360 --> 01:15:08.930
♪ But when you call me... ♪

01:15:08.930 --> 01:15:11.130
♪ Call me Ms. ♪

01:15:11.130 --> 01:15:14.600
STEINEM:
It just seemed as if they were
just trying to keep the lid on.

01:15:14.600 --> 01:15:18.260
You know, they were just hoping
against hope that...

01:15:18.260 --> 01:15:20.760
that somehow there wouldn't be
too many demonstrations

01:15:20.760 --> 01:15:24.360
or that the contestants wouldn't
stand up and, uh, raise a fist.

01:15:24.360 --> 01:15:28.360
You know, somehow the people
who ran the pageant

01:15:28.360 --> 01:15:30.330
were trying desperately
to preserve it.

01:15:30.330 --> 01:15:35.100
♪ I said if you want me,
you gotta call me ♪

01:15:35.100 --> 01:15:39.360
♪ But when you call me... ♪

01:15:39.360 --> 01:15:42.600
♪ Call me Ms. ♪

01:15:42.600 --> 01:15:47.330
(<i> music winding down</i> )

01:15:47.330 --> 01:15:50.830
NARRATOR:
The time had come for
a new-style Miss America

01:15:50.830 --> 01:15:53.460
and in 1973,
the pageant found one

01:15:53.460 --> 01:15:56.960
in an aspiring attorney
from Denver, Colorado

01:15:56.960 --> 01:15:59.460
named Rebecca Ann King.

01:15:59.460 --> 01:16:03.600
KING:
I started watching the Miss
America Pageant as a young girl

01:16:03.600 --> 01:16:06.830
and I wasn't really sure that
it was the kind of young woman

01:16:06.830 --> 01:16:08.100
that I was going to be,

01:16:08.100 --> 01:16:09.600
because I knew I was going to be

01:16:09.600 --> 01:16:11.460
President of the United States
someday.

01:16:11.460 --> 01:16:13.960
The young women looked
a little Barbie-dollish to me.

01:16:13.960 --> 01:16:16.660
They looked a little
too made- up,

01:16:16.660 --> 01:16:18.900
a little too "world peace,"

01:16:18.900 --> 01:16:21.560
and I just didn't think
I was that kind of young woman.

01:16:21.560 --> 01:16:24.530
NARRATOR:
King was finishing up
her senior year

01:16:24.530 --> 01:16:28.430
at Colorado Women's College,
when a friend tried to talk her

01:16:28.430 --> 01:16:30.960
into entering
the Miss America Pageant.

01:16:30.960 --> 01:16:32.430
I said, "What's in it for me?"

01:16:32.430 --> 01:16:34.200
She said,
"There's scholarship money

01:16:34.200 --> 01:16:35.800
so you can go on to law school."

01:16:35.800 --> 01:16:39.530
And so I said,
"Okay, I'll think about it,

01:16:39.530 --> 01:16:41.730
but don't tell anybody."

01:16:41.730 --> 01:16:43.300
(<i> music playing quietly</i> )

01:16:43.300 --> 01:16:48.300
ANNOUNCER:
Rebecca Ann King, Miss Colorado.

01:16:48.300 --> 01:16:52.460
During the past 23 years, my
grandmother often said to me

01:16:52.460 --> 01:16:55.860
that the character of a nation
is determined by its womanhood.

01:16:55.860 --> 01:16:57.830
Through the practice of law,

01:16:57.830 --> 01:17:01.500
I hope to make a productive
contribution to mankind,

01:17:01.500 --> 01:17:04.530
and find the happiness
of a fulfilled woman.

01:17:04.530 --> 01:17:06.600
DREMAN:
I was really in it
for the money.

01:17:06.600 --> 01:17:08.500
And I think
it shocked the pageant

01:17:08.500 --> 01:17:10.130
that I said
I was in it for the money.

01:17:10.130 --> 01:17:11.760
I didn't think
it was strange at all.

01:17:11.760 --> 01:17:14.160
I said, "What is it, it's
a scholarship program, right?

01:17:14.160 --> 01:17:15.630
Isn't that what we're here for?"

01:17:15.630 --> 01:17:22.130
PARKS:
The winner
of a $15,000 scholarship

01:17:22.130 --> 01:17:24.260
and our new Miss America,

01:17:24.260 --> 01:17:26.960
Rebecca Ann King,
Miss Colorado!

01:17:26.960 --> 01:17:35.660
(<i> cheering and applause</i> )

01:17:35.660 --> 01:17:38.200
PARKS:
Any words
for your subjects?

01:17:38.200 --> 01:17:39.830
Very surprised.

01:17:39.830 --> 01:17:41.900
Very surprised
and, undoubtedly,
very happy.

01:17:41.900 --> 01:17:43.300
Thank you very much.

01:17:43.300 --> 01:17:46.400
The new Miss America,
here she comes!

01:17:46.400 --> 01:17:53.330
(<i> Miss America theme playing</i> )

01:17:53.330 --> 01:17:57.230
DREMAN:
I didn't
fall apart as Miss America;

01:17:57.230 --> 01:18:00.230
Walked over, got the crown on.

01:18:00.230 --> 01:18:03.130
And I think my mother received,
hmm, maybe 100 letters

01:18:03.130 --> 01:18:04.730
because I didn't cry.

01:18:04.730 --> 01:18:06.500
"She didn't cry.

01:18:06.500 --> 01:18:09.460
"What kind of Miss America
do we have here on our hands

01:18:09.460 --> 01:18:11.400
walking down the runway
not crying?"

01:18:14.200 --> 01:18:18.260
NARRATOR:
For most Americans,
the real surprise came later,

01:18:18.260 --> 01:18:22.000
when the new Miss America
began speaking to the press

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:25.100
and came out in favor
of legalized abortion.

01:18:25.100 --> 01:18:28.060
DREMAN:
It was right at the time
of Roe v. Wade.

01:18:28.060 --> 01:18:31.460
I thought a woman ought
to have the right to choose

01:18:31.460 --> 01:18:35.360
whether to continue
with a pregnancy or not.

01:18:35.360 --> 01:18:38.730
And, um... it just...
blew completely up

01:18:38.730 --> 01:18:42.560
and the pageant
never said not talk about it.

01:18:42.560 --> 01:18:45.700
PEISS:
Well, the Miss America Pageant
in the 1970s

01:18:45.700 --> 01:18:48.830
is faced with the growing
politicization of women

01:18:48.830 --> 01:18:50.860
on both the left and the right.

01:18:50.860 --> 01:18:53.600
And one of the key moments,
of course,

01:18:53.600 --> 01:18:57.260
is the Roe v. Wade Supreme Court
decision in 1973.

01:18:57.260 --> 01:19:00.360
So when Miss America comes out
as pro-choice,

01:19:00.360 --> 01:19:03.300
inserting a political stand
in the pageant,

01:19:03.300 --> 01:19:07.330
which had always seen itself
as nonpolitical or apolitical,

01:19:07.330 --> 01:19:09.730
it really is
an important moment.

01:19:11.460 --> 01:19:14.760
DREMAN:
The pageant has always been
a little behind the times,

01:19:14.760 --> 01:19:17.030
but it was definitely the '70s.

01:19:17.030 --> 01:19:21.260
It was time for people to move
on, and the pageant was trying.

01:19:21.260 --> 01:19:23.630
ALL:
♪ Moving on... ♪

01:19:23.630 --> 01:19:27.060
♪ Moving on... ♪

01:19:27.060 --> 01:19:30.260
♪ We've got to be moving on... ♪

01:19:30.260 --> 01:19:34.260
NARRATOR:
The national press applauded
Miss America's new image.

01:19:34.260 --> 01:19:38.060
Even feminists, who had been
protesting against the pageant

01:19:38.060 --> 01:19:40.800
for half a decade,
now called off their war

01:19:40.800 --> 01:19:42.960
and invited King to speak

01:19:42.960 --> 01:19:46.930
at the National Organization
for Women's annual convention.

01:19:46.930 --> 01:19:51.630
Still, Miss America's television
audience continued to shrink,

01:19:51.630 --> 01:19:55.260
edged out by competition
from new cable networks

01:19:55.260 --> 01:19:58.930
and dismissed by younger viewers
as old-fashioned.

01:19:58.930 --> 01:20:01.660
(<i> rock music playing</i> )

01:20:01.660 --> 01:20:04.260
HORN:
I think that a large number
of people

01:20:04.260 --> 01:20:07.000
began not watching
the Miss American Pageant

01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:10.830
probably about the mid-70s.

01:20:10.830 --> 01:20:14.330
The ideals upon which the Miss
America pageant appeared to rest

01:20:14.330 --> 01:20:18.330
no longer seemed
very exciting or relevant.

01:20:18.330 --> 01:20:22.300
And I think we lost
a generation of people.

01:20:22.300 --> 01:20:24.730
(<i> fast music playing</i> )

01:20:24.730 --> 01:20:26.700
NARRATOR:
By the late 1970s,

01:20:26.700 --> 01:20:29.900
pageant organizers
were desperate for viewers

01:20:29.900 --> 01:20:33.200
and casting about
for ways to update the show,

01:20:33.200 --> 01:20:35.830
so they decided
to fire Bert Parks,

01:20:35.830 --> 01:20:38.460
Miss America's
master of ceremonies

01:20:38.460 --> 01:20:40.560
for a quarter of a century.

01:20:40.560 --> 01:20:42.100
It was later reported

01:20:42.100 --> 01:20:46.130
that the pageant's sponsors
considered 65-year-old Parks

01:20:46.130 --> 01:20:48.260
too old and too out of touch.

01:20:48.260 --> 01:20:50.660
The decision caused
such an uproar

01:20:50.660 --> 01:20:53.260
that<i> Tonight Show</i>
host Johnny Carson

01:20:53.260 --> 01:20:57.200
even held an on-air campaign
to get Parks reinstated.

01:20:57.200 --> 01:20:59.660
The pageant replaced him anyway.

01:20:59.660 --> 01:21:03.430
But a new host
did not bring new viewers.

01:21:03.430 --> 01:21:06.860
ROSE:
I was a teenager
in the late '70s,

01:21:06.860 --> 01:21:09.460
and I, um... my recollection
of the pageant

01:21:09.460 --> 01:21:11.730
was that it just...
being a New Yorker

01:21:11.730 --> 01:21:15.600
it just didn't seem to reflect
what the city looked like to me.

01:21:15.600 --> 01:21:19.330
So the pageant was a sort
of helpful travelscape for me

01:21:19.330 --> 01:21:22.600
like, oh, this is what women
look like in Texas and Florida.

01:21:22.600 --> 01:21:24.400
I was pretty much sure

01:21:24.400 --> 01:21:27.200
that the most blonde was going
to be in the top two

01:21:27.200 --> 01:21:28.700
if not the number one slot.

01:21:28.700 --> 01:21:30.460
If a brunette was going to win,

01:21:30.460 --> 01:21:33.160
it was because of some other
extraordinary traits

01:21:33.160 --> 01:21:36.100
that were compensating,
but I very much understood it

01:21:36.100 --> 01:21:39.200
as a tall, blonde, you know,
Southern women's festival.

01:21:39.200 --> 01:21:41.900
PARKS:
Miss Tennessee.

01:21:41.900 --> 01:21:44.200
CHO:
My father was very into it.

01:21:44.200 --> 01:21:46.430
And then, at one point
when I was a little girl,

01:21:46.430 --> 01:21:48.500
I said, "I want to be
one of those contestants.

01:21:48.500 --> 01:21:50.560
I want to grow up and do that."

01:21:50.560 --> 01:21:52.230
And he said, "No, oh, no,

01:21:52.230 --> 01:21:53.830
you cannot do that, no."

01:21:53.830 --> 01:21:55.760
You know, like...

01:21:55.760 --> 01:21:57.830
And I took it to mean

01:21:57.830 --> 01:22:00.230
that the beauty pageant
was not open to all women.

01:22:00.230 --> 01:22:02.360
I mean, my father thought

01:22:02.360 --> 01:22:04.160
that this whole pageant
was fascinating

01:22:04.160 --> 01:22:07.760
and we would pick out the
winners, but I was not allowed

01:22:07.760 --> 01:22:11.230
to even entertain the fantasy
of becoming one of these women.

01:22:11.230 --> 01:22:13.460
And I thought, "Maybe
I'm just not pretty enough.

01:22:13.460 --> 01:22:14.930
Or maybe I'm just not white."

01:22:14.930 --> 01:22:17.260
I remember always sitting
in front of the television

01:22:17.260 --> 01:22:19.200
watching the Miss America
every single year

01:22:19.200 --> 01:22:21.800
when I was a little kid,
and I was the only one watching.

01:22:21.800 --> 01:22:23.300
Everybody else
kind of went to bed,

01:22:23.300 --> 01:22:24.700
and I would be so excited.

01:22:24.700 --> 01:22:26.430
"Mom, I chose
the first runner up

01:22:26.430 --> 01:22:27.660
or the second runner up."


01:22:27.660 --> 01:22:29.260
But the interesting thing
about that,

01:22:29.260 --> 01:22:32.330
I always kind of saw myself
on stage as well,

01:22:32.330 --> 01:22:34.530
although no one looked like me;

01:22:34.530 --> 01:22:36.460
there was no one
who looked like me.

01:22:36.460 --> 01:22:38.530
(<i> music playing</i> )

01:22:38.530 --> 01:22:40.060
PARKS:
Miss Iowa.

01:22:40.060 --> 01:22:44.400
NARRATOR:
20-year-old Cheryl Brown,
Miss Iowa 1970,

01:22:44.400 --> 01:22:46.960
had been the first
African-American woman

01:22:46.960 --> 01:22:49.060
ever to compete
in Atlantic City.

01:22:49.060 --> 01:22:50.660
(<i> applause</i> )

01:22:50.660 --> 01:22:52.460
In the decade that followed,

01:22:52.460 --> 01:22:55.800
there had been just
ten other black contestants

01:22:55.800 --> 01:23:00.400
and of those, only one
had made the top five:

01:23:00.400 --> 01:23:02.330
Lencola Sullivan,
Miss Arkansas 1980.

01:23:02.330 --> 01:23:05.800
SULLIVAN:
I made history that night by
being the first black woman

01:23:05.800 --> 01:23:08.500
to ever make top five
in the Miss America Pageant.

01:23:08.500 --> 01:23:10.500
And even though
that was wonderful,

01:23:10.500 --> 01:23:13.560
of course, I was sad that
I didn't make it to the top

01:23:13.560 --> 01:23:17.030
and didn't walk away with the...
the title of Miss America.

01:23:17.030 --> 01:23:20.100
ANNOUNCER:
Fourth runner-up and winner
of a $5,000 scholarship is...

01:23:20.100 --> 01:23:23.230
SULLIVAN:
That was actually one of the
questions that was asked of me

01:23:23.230 --> 01:23:25.200
when I competed, was

01:23:25.200 --> 01:23:28.330
"Is America ready for a black
woman to become Miss America?"

01:23:28.330 --> 01:23:31.130
And I said, "If Arkansas
is ready, America is ready,"

01:23:31.130 --> 01:23:35.130
but, obviously,
America wasn't ready.

01:23:35.130 --> 01:23:41.230
NARRATOR:
But in 1983, the 61st year
of the Miss America Pageant,

01:23:41.230 --> 01:23:43.860
everything suddenly changed.

01:23:43.860 --> 01:23:45.960
(<i> sultry music playing</i> )

01:23:45.960 --> 01:23:52.160
♪ Happy days are here again ♪

01:23:52.160 --> 01:23:56.500
♪ The skies above
are clear again... ♪

01:23:56.500 --> 01:23:58.530
ANNOUNCER:
And our new Miss America

01:23:58.530 --> 01:24:01.100
is Vanessa Williams,
Miss New York!

01:24:01.100 --> 01:24:04.060
(<i> cheering and applause</i> )

01:24:04.060 --> 01:24:11.100
WILLIAMS:
♪ Happy days are here again... ♪

01:24:11.100 --> 01:24:14.800
NARRATOR:
A 20-year-old musical theater
major at Syracuse University,

01:24:14.800 --> 01:24:16.560
Williams had entered the pageant

01:24:16.560 --> 01:24:18.900
in the hope of breaking
into show business.

01:24:18.900 --> 01:24:22.060
Like so many Miss Americas
before her,

01:24:22.060 --> 01:24:24.830
she wanted to be a star.

01:24:24.830 --> 01:24:27.430
But first, she would become
a political symbol.

01:24:27.430 --> 01:24:31.100
WILLIAMS:
♪ The skies above
are clear again ♪

01:24:31.100 --> 01:24:32.700
♪ So let's sing a song... ♪

01:24:32.700 --> 01:24:35.930
NARRATOR:
To some, the crowning
of a black Miss America

01:24:35.930 --> 01:24:39.000
was a milestone in the struggle
against bigotry.

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:41.430
"Thank God I have lived
long enough,"

01:24:41.430 --> 01:24:43.800
said Congresswoman
Shirley Chisholm,

01:24:43.800 --> 01:24:46.300
"that this nation
has been able to select

01:24:46.300 --> 01:24:49.730
the beautiful young woman
of color to be Miss America."

01:24:49.730 --> 01:24:55.660
WILLIAMS:
♪ Again... ♪

01:24:55.660 --> 01:24:59.100
(<i> applause</i> )

01:24:59.100 --> 01:25:02.030
WOMAN:
That was the first time I
remember watching Miss America,

01:25:02.030 --> 01:25:06.630
and I remember her singing,
I remember her performance,

01:25:06.630 --> 01:25:09.100
I remember her being crowned,

01:25:09.100 --> 01:25:13.300
and I remember thinking,
"Wow, she looks like me."

01:25:13.300 --> 01:25:16.200
I had never at that point,
I had heard of Miss America,

01:25:16.200 --> 01:25:19.100
but I had never at that point
thought that Miss America

01:25:19.100 --> 01:25:22.230
was something that was for me
or something that I could do.

01:25:22.230 --> 01:25:25.160
I think everybody
was shocked, excited

01:25:25.160 --> 01:25:28.360
and just looking forward
to having a year

01:25:28.360 --> 01:25:31.900
where there was a Miss America
that was black

01:25:31.900 --> 01:25:33.800
and would get to do
all the great things

01:25:33.800 --> 01:25:35.900
that every other Miss America
had ever done.

01:25:35.900 --> 01:25:40.430
So I think it was just a time
of excitement and anticipation.

01:25:42.660 --> 01:25:47.430
NARRATOR:
Williams' fans made her the most
heavily-booked Miss America

01:25:47.430 --> 01:25:49.630
in the pageant's history.

01:25:49.630 --> 01:25:52.930
Not quite ten months
into her reign,

01:25:52.930 --> 01:25:57.430
she had already earned
a record $125,000 in fees.

01:25:57.430 --> 01:26:00.700
I remember talking
to some pageant people

01:26:00.700 --> 01:26:03.960
and they said that the best
Miss America they ever had

01:26:03.960 --> 01:26:05.300
was Vanessa Williams.

01:26:05.300 --> 01:26:06.900
She was just sensational.

01:26:06.900 --> 01:26:10.260
She was just the most verbal,
bright, terrific seller

01:26:10.260 --> 01:26:13.060
of the Miss America contest
they'd ever had.

01:26:13.060 --> 01:26:15.260
NARRATOR:
But there were those

01:26:15.260 --> 01:26:18.600
who considered
Williams' victory an affront.

01:26:18.600 --> 01:26:20.030
For the first time,

01:26:20.030 --> 01:26:23.800
Miss America received
death threats and hate mail.

01:26:23.800 --> 01:26:26.630
When she made appearances
in the south,

01:26:26.630 --> 01:26:30.530
armed guards had to be posted
at her hotel room door.

01:26:30.530 --> 01:26:33.430
And even in
the African-American community,

01:26:33.430 --> 01:26:35.660
there were
those who assailed her

01:26:35.660 --> 01:26:37.700
for not being "black" enough.

01:26:37.700 --> 01:26:39.830
Then, in July of 1984,

01:26:39.830 --> 01:26:44.930
Williams was informed
that an unauthorized pictorial,

01:26:44.930 --> 01:26:46.900
featuring explicit nude photos

01:26:46.900 --> 01:26:49.200
she had posed for
two years earlier,

01:26:49.200 --> 01:26:53.230
was about to be published
in<i> Penthouse</i> magazine.

01:26:53.230 --> 01:26:58.030
Pageant officials
were quick to respond.

01:26:58.030 --> 01:27:01.530
We do not believe under the
content and spirit of the rules,

01:27:01.530 --> 01:27:05.060
as well as the contracts as well
as the image of Miss America,

01:27:05.060 --> 01:27:07.060
that she should remain
Miss America

01:27:07.060 --> 01:27:09.230
and still give
this particular program

01:27:09.230 --> 01:27:12.260
the vitality and the respect
to which it's entitled.

01:27:12.260 --> 01:27:13.730
If you don't
draw the line here,

01:27:13.730 --> 01:27:15.360
where do you
draw the line?

01:27:15.360 --> 01:27:18.460
HORN:
The sponsors were waiting
on the sidelines.

01:27:18.460 --> 01:27:22.530
We had received a warning that
if we didn't handle this right,

01:27:22.530 --> 01:27:24.560
they were going to pull out.

01:27:24.560 --> 01:27:26.600
If they'd pulled out
at the end of July,

01:27:26.600 --> 01:27:29.660
there would've been no money and
no Miss America Pageant in 1984.

01:27:29.660 --> 01:27:32.160
And there would not be
a Miss America Pageant today.

01:27:32.160 --> 01:27:33.800
That's how close we came.

01:27:33.800 --> 01:27:37.530
NARRATOR:
Williams was given
72 hours to resign.

01:27:37.530 --> 01:27:41.030
She would be allowed
to keep her scholarship

01:27:41.030 --> 01:27:43.430
and the money she had earned,

01:27:43.430 --> 01:27:46.660
but her title would be given
to the first runner-up,

01:27:46.660 --> 01:27:48.530
Suzette Charles.

01:27:48.530 --> 01:27:52.130
WOMAN:
It is one thing to face up to a
mistake that one makes in youth.

01:27:52.130 --> 01:27:55.900
But it is almost totally
devastating to have to share it

01:27:55.900 --> 01:27:59.030
with the American public
and the world at large

01:27:59.030 --> 01:28:01.930
as both a human being
and as Miss America.

01:28:01.930 --> 01:28:04.200
I put the session
in the back of my mind

01:28:04.200 --> 01:28:07.630
and believed the photos would
never be used for any purpose,

01:28:07.630 --> 01:28:10.160
as the photographer
had verbally assured me.

01:28:10.160 --> 01:28:13.430
I never consented
to the publication

01:28:13.430 --> 01:28:17.660
or the use of these photographs
in any manner.

01:28:17.660 --> 01:28:22.300
NARRATOR:
It was the first time in
the pageant's six-decade history

01:28:22.300 --> 01:28:25.900
that a Miss America
was asked to give up her crown.

01:28:25.900 --> 01:28:28.960
COCKERHAM:
I think a lot of people
were very disappointed.

01:28:28.960 --> 01:28:31.530
And I think
any minority community

01:28:31.530 --> 01:28:35.160
looks to their role models
that are so accepted

01:28:35.160 --> 01:28:37.460
and are so loved by everybody

01:28:37.460 --> 01:28:41.900
as a point of,
you know, inspiration,

01:28:41.900 --> 01:28:46.160
and maybe at that point it is,
you are let down,

01:28:46.160 --> 01:28:48.930
that, okay, these
are choices that she made

01:28:48.930 --> 01:28:51.430
that have caused a lot
of embarrassment

01:28:51.430 --> 01:28:55.030
to her and her family,
but also to the black community.

01:28:55.030 --> 01:28:58.930
ROSE:
I do remember feeling, you know,
incredibly sorry for her.

01:28:58.930 --> 01:29:01.730
I just felt that she
was carrying the weight

01:29:01.730 --> 01:29:05.600
of this whole history of vicious
stereotypes about black women,

01:29:05.600 --> 01:29:08.900
and simply by trying
to win the pageant,

01:29:08.900 --> 01:29:10.430
she was, in a sense,

01:29:10.430 --> 01:29:14.130
trying to counter
many of those stereotypes.

01:29:14.130 --> 01:29:15.630
And then, you know,

01:29:15.630 --> 01:29:17.930
to have these pictures emerge
to undermine it

01:29:17.930 --> 01:29:20.760
was, you know, probably
the most vicious way to have it,

01:29:20.760 --> 01:29:22.660
because, you know,
I would be stunned

01:29:22.660 --> 01:29:24.700
if she was
the first pageant contestant

01:29:24.700 --> 01:29:26.760
to have tried
to raise money as a model

01:29:26.760 --> 01:29:28.530
by doing
these kinds of pictures.

01:29:28.530 --> 01:29:30.000
I would be really shocked.

01:29:30.000 --> 01:29:31.530
But I wouldn't be surprised

01:29:31.530 --> 01:29:35.060
if people were more interested
in finding hers to undermine it

01:29:35.060 --> 01:29:37.300
because she, in a sense,
by definition,

01:29:37.300 --> 01:29:40.060
threw the rest of the
contestants into stark relief.

01:29:42.060 --> 01:29:45.130
NARRATOR:
The Vanessa Williams issue
of<i> Penthouse</i>

01:29:45.130 --> 01:29:47.800
would ultimately bring in
over $20 million,

01:29:47.800 --> 01:29:51.030
the magazine's all-time,
single-issue sales record.

01:29:51.030 --> 01:29:53.500
CHO:
You know, what's
great about it is

01:29:53.500 --> 01:29:57.200
that she's the only Miss America
that anybody remembers,

01:29:57.200 --> 01:30:00.800
and she's the only one
that ever really became a star.

01:30:00.800 --> 01:30:05.560
And... and... uh, that is
what's really great,

01:30:05.560 --> 01:30:11.500
is that she has the most
"Kiss my ass" story--

01:30:11.500 --> 01:30:14.330
that... that you can
triumph over anything.

01:30:14.330 --> 01:30:16.830
So she's certainly
a big hero of mine.

01:30:19.660 --> 01:30:22.800
NARRATOR:
For a time, the scandal
revived public interest

01:30:22.800 --> 01:30:24.430
in the Miss America Pageant,

01:30:24.430 --> 01:30:30.030
and ticket sales for the 1984
finals rose by 20%.

01:30:30.030 --> 01:30:34.260
That night, after only
two months as Miss America,

01:30:34.260 --> 01:30:37.430
Suzette Charles walked
the Convention Hall runway

01:30:37.430 --> 01:30:40.830
to a standing ovation
before crowning her successor,

01:30:40.830 --> 01:30:46.100
20-year-old Sharlene Wells,
a tall, blonde Mormon

01:30:46.100 --> 01:30:50.860
whom USA Today described
as "squeaky-clean."

01:30:50.860 --> 01:30:56.800
EMCEE:
♪ Miss America... ♪

01:30:56.800 --> 01:31:00.530
(<i> applause and cheering</i> )

01:31:00.530 --> 01:31:04.400
CHORUS:
♪ I can fly, I can fly,
I can fly, I can fly... ♪

01:31:04.400 --> 01:31:07.700
NARRATOR:
Confronted now by
the possibility of scandals

01:31:07.700 --> 01:31:10.630
that Lenora Slaughter
never could have imagined,

01:31:10.630 --> 01:31:14.930
pageant directors drew up
a new contestant contract,

01:31:14.930 --> 01:31:17.060
gradually adding
dozens of regulations

01:31:17.060 --> 01:31:19.660
to which potential Miss Americas
were subject.

01:31:19.660 --> 01:31:21.330
CHORUS:
♪ I can fly! ♪

01:31:21.330 --> 01:31:23.300
WOMAN:
That you've always
been female, is one.

01:31:23.300 --> 01:31:24.700
Isn't that hilarious?

01:31:24.700 --> 01:31:26.960
You have to sign
a contract saying,

01:31:26.960 --> 01:31:28.660
"I've always been female."

01:31:28.660 --> 01:31:30.260
There's a clause in the contract

01:31:30.260 --> 01:31:32.130
that you have never
posed in the nude.

01:31:32.130 --> 01:31:33.660
There's also a clause
that you can't

01:31:33.660 --> 01:31:35.600
be the natural
or adoptive parent of a child.

01:31:35.600 --> 01:31:37.430
And then there
is a clause in the contract

01:31:37.430 --> 01:31:39.060
that you have never
done anything

01:31:39.060 --> 01:31:41.430
that could possibly
be interpreted as illegal,

01:31:41.430 --> 01:31:42.930
immoral, unethical, whatever.

01:31:42.930 --> 01:31:45.230
And, you know,
everybody signs the contract,

01:31:45.230 --> 01:31:47.760
but who didn't cheat
on a second grade math test?

01:31:47.760 --> 01:31:52.100
NARRATOR:
With the changes in the contract
came a renewed campaign

01:31:52.100 --> 01:31:55.160
to portray Miss America
as a "thinking woman,"

01:31:55.160 --> 01:31:59.000
who would make a positive
contribution to society.

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:03.400
In 1989,
pageant officials introduced

01:32:03.400 --> 01:32:05.700
a new competitive element
called "the platform,"

01:32:05.700 --> 01:32:07.030
which required contestants

01:32:07.030 --> 01:32:08.900
to demonstrate
an ongoing commitment

01:32:08.900 --> 01:32:11.230
to a social problem

01:32:11.230 --> 01:32:14.030
and to back it up
with community service.

01:32:14.030 --> 01:32:15.800
Hello from the Sunshine State.

01:32:15.800 --> 01:32:17.600
I'm devoted to promoting unity

01:32:17.600 --> 01:32:20.530
through the celebration
of our cultural diversity.

01:32:20.530 --> 01:32:22.760
I am devoted
to encouraging youth

01:32:22.760 --> 01:32:25.230
to postpone
their sexual activity.

01:32:25.230 --> 01:32:28.230
My personal commitment
is to child abuse prevention

01:32:28.230 --> 01:32:30.130
through my program, TRUST.

01:32:30.130 --> 01:32:31.500
SHINDLE:
One of those things

01:32:31.500 --> 01:32:32.700
people love to make fun of.

01:32:32.700 --> 01:32:34.330
"I'd love to...
I support world peace

01:32:34.330 --> 01:32:36.030
and I want to give
everyone a flower."

01:32:38.460 --> 01:32:39.900
During my year as Miss America,

01:32:39.900 --> 01:32:42.300
because I was talking
about AIDS, which was something

01:32:42.300 --> 01:32:45.130
that people don't necessarily
associate with the conservative,

01:32:45.130 --> 01:32:47.600
white bread, grass roots,
Miss America organization,

01:32:47.600 --> 01:32:49.330
it got a lot of media attention.

01:32:49.330 --> 01:32:53.800
I took some flack for talking to
students about sexual activity,

01:32:53.800 --> 01:32:56.760
certainly about abstinence,
but also about safer sex.

01:32:56.760 --> 01:32:59.600
There are people who don't want
you to come to their high school

01:32:59.600 --> 01:33:01.360
and say things like that.

01:33:01.360 --> 01:33:04.230
But I will tell you that Miss
America got me so much access.

01:33:04.230 --> 01:33:06.460
The fact that I was
invited to speak

01:33:06.460 --> 01:33:09.230
at middle and high schools
in middle America

01:33:09.230 --> 01:33:10.860
where they would<i> never,</i>

01:33:10.860 --> 01:33:14.830
never invite an AIDS activist to
come and speak to their kids--

01:33:14.830 --> 01:33:17.300
but they'll roll out
the red carpet for Miss America

01:33:17.300 --> 01:33:19.760
and hope she brings her crown--
was an enormous part

01:33:19.760 --> 01:33:22.830
of what I felt was effective
during that year.

01:33:22.830 --> 01:33:26.500
ANNOUNCER:
Live, from Atlantic City,

01:33:26.500 --> 01:33:29.600
ABC proudly presents
"Miss America."

01:33:29.600 --> 01:33:38.800
(<i> cheering and applause</i> )

01:33:38.800 --> 01:33:41.060
WOMAN:
I would love
for everyone to join hands

01:33:41.060 --> 01:33:44.330
and we'll say a little prayer.

01:33:46.060 --> 01:33:47.500
NARRATOR:
More than 80 years

01:33:47.500 --> 01:33:50.160
after the first contest
was held in Atlantic City,

01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:52.730
the Miss America Pageant
still endures.

01:33:52.730 --> 01:33:54.960
WOMAN:
We come here in friendship,

01:33:54.960 --> 01:33:57.500
one in community
and one in service...

01:33:57.500 --> 01:34:02.160
NARRATOR:
It is one of the longest-running
television programs

01:34:02.160 --> 01:34:06.300
in American history, seen
by more than a billion people

01:34:06.300 --> 01:34:08.860
since its first broadcast
in 1954.

01:34:08.860 --> 01:34:12.560
It is also the single largest
scholarship organization

01:34:12.560 --> 01:34:14.200
for women in the world.

01:34:14.200 --> 01:34:17.060
Each year,
1,200 state and local pageants

01:34:17.060 --> 01:34:20.500
are franchised by
the Miss America Organization.

01:34:20.500 --> 01:34:23.530
And each year,
more than 10,000 young women

01:34:23.530 --> 01:34:26.430
enter those contests,
all of them hoping

01:34:26.430 --> 01:34:29.860
Miss America's crown
will change their lives.


01:34:29.860 --> 01:34:32.360
So with that
in Jesus' name we pray.

01:34:32.360 --> 01:34:34.360
Amen.

01:34:34.360 --> 01:34:35.600
Go, girls,
you go out there

01:34:35.600 --> 01:34:36.700
and get them,
all right?

01:34:36.700 --> 01:34:41.600
(<i> applause and cheers</i> )

01:34:41.600 --> 01:34:42.900
Good luck.

01:34:42.900 --> 01:34:44.230
Good luck.

01:34:44.230 --> 01:34:46.000
MAN:
One minute folks.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:47.530
One minute to air.

01:34:47.530 --> 01:34:49.060
WOMAN:
60 seconds.

01:34:49.060 --> 01:34:50.660
(<i> percussion thundering</i> )

01:34:50.660 --> 01:34:52.900
(<i> contestants cheering</i> )

01:34:52.900 --> 01:34:56.160
COCKERHAM:
I think every contestant
that comes to Miss America

01:34:56.160 --> 01:34:57.430
has a different agenda.

01:34:57.430 --> 01:34:58.830
Some contestants come there

01:34:58.830 --> 01:35:01.700
because they want to be
discovered by a modeling agency

01:35:01.700 --> 01:35:04.130
or they want to go into acting
or broadcasting.

01:35:04.130 --> 01:35:07.030
Many contestants go because
of their social activism.

01:35:07.030 --> 01:35:09.700
Many contestants go
just because they have this idea

01:35:09.700 --> 01:35:12.600
of Miss America with the crown
walking down the runway.

01:35:12.600 --> 01:35:17.560
(<i> up-tempo instrumental version
 of "Miss America" playing</i> )

01:35:17.560 --> 01:35:19.560
(<i> applause and cheering</i> )

01:35:34.500 --> 01:35:38.160
WOMAN:
I would love to be
your next Miss America.

01:35:38.160 --> 01:35:41.530
It would give me the opportunity

01:35:41.530 --> 01:35:46.260
to represent
many wonderful people.

01:35:46.260 --> 01:35:48.100
It would also enable me

01:35:48.100 --> 01:35:52.100
to further my education
at Sacramento State College.

01:35:52.100 --> 01:35:55.760
It would give me the opportunity
to meet many wonderful people

01:35:55.760 --> 01:35:59.860
which I wouldn't otherwise
have the opportunity of meeting.

01:35:59.860 --> 01:36:05.000
It would also considerably
broaden my outlook on life.

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:08.660
I would love to be
your next Miss America.

01:36:33.000 --> 01:36:36.030
(<i> cheering and applause</i> )

01:36:42.260 --> 01:36:44.300
CHO:
I think that women's roles

01:36:44.300 --> 01:36:47.100
have changed so much
in the last 20 years,

01:36:47.100 --> 01:36:49.160
that we are constantly looking

01:36:49.160 --> 01:36:52.160
for the outside world
to tell us who we are.

01:36:53.830 --> 01:36:57.200
We really search
for this "for-sure" identity,

01:36:57.200 --> 01:37:01.100
for this "for-sure"
being of who we are,

01:37:01.100 --> 01:37:05.930
and the pageant is one way
of defining ourselves.

01:37:08.060 --> 01:37:09.660
GOLDMAN:
I wonder, I don't know.

01:37:09.660 --> 01:37:11.630
Do little girls now
of six and seven

01:37:11.630 --> 01:37:13.230
dream of being Miss America?

01:37:13.230 --> 01:37:14.530
I don't know.

01:37:14.530 --> 01:37:16.460
Or do they dream
of replacing Bill Gates?

01:37:16.460 --> 01:37:17.460
I have no idea.

01:37:20.030 --> 01:37:22.500
BANET-WEISER:
It's not you either love it
or you hate it,

01:37:22.500 --> 01:37:25.330
it's not
it's either good or bad.

01:37:25.330 --> 01:37:29.700
It just doesn't fit that neatly
into one of those boxes.

01:37:29.700 --> 01:37:35.200
I think that what civic rituals
do is that they are stories

01:37:35.200 --> 01:37:37.260
that we tell ourselves
about ourselves.

01:37:37.260 --> 01:37:39.330
And I think
that along with considering

01:37:39.330 --> 01:37:41.660
the Miss America Pageant
as popular culture,

01:37:41.660 --> 01:37:44.630
we needed to consider it
as about imagining citizenship

01:37:44.630 --> 01:37:49.060
and imagining, who we are, why
we're here, and what we're for.

